<paragraph blockId="43.[151,820,1408,1467]" box="[151,820,1408,1434]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,820,1408,1434]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,820,1408,1434]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<taxonomicName authority="Hoge, 1853" authorityName="Hoge" authorityYear="1853" box="[151,555,1408,1434]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Lygophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paucidens">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,390,1408,1434]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Lygophis paucidens</emphasis>
(Hoge, 
<number box="[487,547,1408,1434]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" value="1853.0">1853</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
“Cobra-de-cadarço”
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,820,1408,1467]" box="[151,384,1442,1467]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">(Figs. 16.4 and 29.1)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1514,1683]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
First record in the Caatinga. Recorded only in three localities, in the states of Piauí and Bahia, in altitudes up to 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
elevation. It is found mostly in open savannas and grasslands on sandy soils, and is considered a Cerrado endemic snake (
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" box="[333,570,1586,1611]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" refString="Nogueira, C., Colli, G. R., Costa, G. &amp; Machado, R. B. (2010) Diversidade de repteis Squamata e evolucao do conhecimento faunistico no Cerrado. In: Diniz, I. R., Marinho-Filho, J., Machado, R. B. &amp; Cavalcanti, R. B. (Eds.), Cerrado: conhecimento cientifico quantitativo como subsidio para acoes de conservacao. Editora UNB, Brasilia, pp. 333 - 375." type="book chapter" year="2010">
Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[446,504,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[511,570,1587,1611]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" value="2010.2011">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 2011). It probably occurs in areas with relictual cerrado enclaves, including those in uplands of the Chapada 
<taxonomicName box="[528,659,1622,1647]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="43" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina</taxonomicName>
complex. It has terrestrial habits, is diurnal, and feeds on frogs and lizards (
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[240,379,1658,1683]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" refString="Dixon, J. R. (1989) A key and checklist to the Neotropical snake genus Liophis with country lists and maps. Smithsonian Herpetological Information, 79, 1 - 39. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 23317515.79.1" type="journal article" year="1989">
Dixon 
<number box="[319,379,1659,1683]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
